Note:
============================================================================
WAVE 1 BACKFILL — DISPATCHED-API PROCS
============================================================================
This section backfills the 25 dispatched-API procs that the assembly/syscall.runa
dispatcher routes to but were previously missing from this Linux RISC-V 32-bit
(ilp32) platform module:

  Compatibility bridges (7): SYS_OPEN, SYS_STAT, SYS_LSTAT, SYS_CREAT,
  SYS_UNLINK, SYS_MKDIR, SYS_RMDIR — Linux RISC-V 32-bit uses the asm-generic
  syscall numbering and does NOT expose native syscalls for these legacy
  POSIX names. Each backfilled proc returns the numeric value of the *-at
  family successor that userland wrappers must route through (AT_FDCWD +
  flag modifiers).

  High-level wrappers (2): syscall_fstat, syscall_lseek — the remaining
  Unix-portable function names the cross-platform dispatcher exposes; each
  is a thin shim over the existing syscall_N inline-asm helper with the
  platform-correct syscall number. The other eight syscall_<name> wrappers
  (syscall_read, syscall_write, syscall_open, syscall_close, syscall_exit,
  syscall_brk, syscall_mmap, syscall_munmap) are already present earlier
  in this file.

  POSIX file-mode constants (2): MODE_0644 (rw-r--r-- = decimal 420),
  MODE_0755 (rwxr-xr-x = decimal 493). These are octal POSIX modes
  pre-decoded for callers that pass mode to openat/creat/mkdirat.

  lseek whence constants (3): SEEK_SET, SEEK_CUR, SEEK_END.

  Additional open(2) flag constants (3): O_CREAT, O_TRUNC, O_APPEND. The
  three base access-mode flags (O_RDONLY, O_WRONLY, O_RDWR) are already
  defined earlier in this file.

  Memory protection flags (4): PROT_NONE, PROT_READ, PROT_WRITE, PROT_EXEC.

  Memory mapping flags (4): MAP_SHARED, MAP_PRIVATE, MAP_FIXED, MAP_ANONYMOUS.

Authoritative source for every syscall number: Linux kernel
include/uapi/asm-generic/unistd.h (linux v6.x). RISC-V uses the asm-generic
syscall table directly — there is no arch/riscv-specific override.
Authoritative source for the file/memory flag constants: Linux kernel
include/uapi/asm-generic/fcntl.h (O_*), include/uapi/asm-generic/mman-common.h
(PROT_*, MAP_*), and include/uapi/linux/fs.h (SEEK_*). RISC-V inherits the
asm-generic values unchanged.
:End Note

Note:
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Compatibility bridges (legacy POSIX names -> asm-generic *-at successors)
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
:End Note

Process called "riscv32_SYS_OPEN" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Linux RISC-V 32-bit (asm-generic numbering) does not provide the legacy
    single-path open(2) syscall. Userland that wants open() semantics must
    invoke openat(2) with the special directory file descriptor AT_FDCWD
    (-100), which causes the kernel to resolve relative paths against the
    calling process's current working directory — byte-equivalent to the
    behaviour of the obsolete open(2). The dispatched-API contract requires
    every platform to expose SYS_OPEN; on rv32 we expose it as a routing
    identity: SYS_OPEN returns the openat number (56), and any caller that
    uses this number must construct the syscall arg-list as (AT_FDCWD,
    pathname, flags, mode) rather than the legacy (pathname, flags, mode).

    Reference: Linux kernel include/uapi/asm-generic/unistd.h pins
    __NR_openat at 56 and intentionally omits __NR_open from the
    asm-generic table; RISC-V inherits this numbering directly.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Returns the integer 56, the asm-generic __NR_openat value. Linux
    kernel commit 24eddbe44e63 ("asm-generic: remove legacy file syscalls")
    pinned the numbering. The high-level wrapper syscall_open earlier in
    this file consumes SYS_OPEN's value and (per the dispatcher contract)
    must bridge the 3-arg open() shape to the 4-arg openat() shape by
    prepending AT_FDCWD (-100) to the argument list before invoking
    syscall_4. The current syscall_open shim retains the 3-arg form for
    parity with the dispatcher API surface; Wave 2/3 may extend the shim
    once the dispatcher migrates to the prefixed-name routing scheme.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). Single integer return, inlinable. Kernel-side overhead is
    identical to native open() on architectures that retain it; the
    asm-generic openat() path is the same kernel routine that x86_64's
    open() ultimately dispatches into (do_sys_open in fs/open.c).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No user-provided input handled here. The returned integer is a
    compile-time constant. Security-relevant validation (path canonical
    resolution, permission checks, O_NOFOLLOW handling) is performed by
    the kernel during the actual openat invocation, not by this proc.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 56
End Process

Process called "riscv32_SYS_STAT" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Linux RISC-V 32-bit asm-generic numbering does not provide stat(2).
    The replacement is newfstatat(2) with dirfd=AT_FDCWD and flags=0,
    which yields byte-equivalent semantics to the legacy stat(2) (follow
    symlinks, return file metadata into the supplied struct stat). This
    proc returns the newfstatat syscall number (79); callers that
    reconstruct the legacy stat() shape must construct the syscall
    arg-list as (AT_FDCWD, pathname, statbuf, 0).

    Reference: Linux kernel include/uapi/asm-generic/unistd.h pins
    __NR_newfstatat at 79.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Returns the integer 79, the asm-generic __NR_newfstatat value. The
    rv32 kernel implementation of newfstatat dispatches through
    fs/stat.c::__do_sys_newfstatat (shared with all asm-generic platforms).
    Userland bridging from the 2-arg stat() shape requires injecting
    AT_FDCWD as the first arg and 0 as the trailing flags arg.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). Single integer return. Kernel-side cost is identical to legacy
    stat() (one vfs_statx call); no architectural penalty for using the
    *-at successor on rv32.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No user input. Constant return. The actual stat() permission checks
    (path traversal, search permission on parent directories) happen
    inside the kernel on the live syscall.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 79
End Process

Process called "riscv32_SYS_LSTAT" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Linux RISC-V 32-bit asm-generic numbering does not provide lstat(2).
    The replacement is newfstatat(2) with dirfd=AT_FDCWD and
    flags=AT_SYMLINK_NOFOLLOW (0x100), which causes the kernel to return
    metadata for the symlink itself rather than its target — the defining
    semantic difference between lstat() and stat(). This proc returns the
    newfstatat syscall number (79); callers must construct the syscall
    arg-list as (AT_FDCWD, pathname, statbuf, 0x100) to get the lstat()
    shape.

    Reference: Linux kernel include/uapi/linux/fcntl.h defines
    AT_SYMLINK_NOFOLLOW=0x100.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Returns the integer 79, the asm-generic __NR_newfstatat value (same
    syscall as SYS_STAT — the flag argument differentiates them). The
    bridging discipline at the caller is: (AT_FDCWD, pathname, statbuf,
    AT_SYMLINK_NOFOLLOW). A caller that omits AT_SYMLINK_NOFOLLOW
    silently degrades to stat semantics — a category error this proc
    cannot enforce; the caller-side wrapper must enforce it.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). Same kernel-side cost profile as SYS_STAT; the
    AT_SYMLINK_NOFOLLOW flag is a single conditional branch inside
    vfs_statx.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Returning the right number is a correctness pre-condition for any
    file-permission audit that relies on lstat semantics. A caller that
    receives the right number but fails to pass AT_SYMLINK_NOFOLLOW
    compromises TOCTOU-resistant code that depends on lstat to inspect
    symlinks without traversing them: the call silently degrades to
    stat() semantics and traverses the symlink, defeating the audit.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 79
End Process

Process called "riscv32_SYS_CREAT" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Linux RISC-V 32-bit asm-generic numbering does not provide creat(2).
    The creat(path, mode) call is exactly equivalent to open(path,
    O_WRONLY|O_CREAT|O_TRUNC, mode), and POSIX explicitly defines it that
    way. We expose SYS_CREAT as a routing identity to the openat(2)
    number (56); the high-level wrapper that consumes this value must
    construct the syscall arg-list as (AT_FDCWD, path,
    O_WRONLY|O_CREAT|O_TRUNC, mode).

    Reference: POSIX.1-2017 creat(2): "The creat() function shall behave
    as if implemented as: int creat(const char *path, mode_t mode) {
    return open(path, O_WRONLY | O_CREAT | O_TRUNC, mode); }".
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Returns the integer 56, the asm-generic __NR_openat value. The flag
    composition (O_WRONLY|O_CREAT|O_TRUNC = 1|64|512 = 577 in Linux
    flag encoding on rv32) is the caller's responsibility; this proc
    only provides the syscall-number routing.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). The kernel does not optimize creat() any differently from
    openat() with the equivalent flags; the asm-generic path is the
    canonical one.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No input processing here. The mode argument the caller supplies to
    the eventual openat() call is masked by the process umask (a
    standard POSIX permission interaction); that mask is applied by the
    kernel, not by this proc.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 56
End Process

Process called "riscv32_SYS_UNLINK" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Linux RISC-V 32-bit asm-generic numbering does not provide unlink(2).
    The replacement is unlinkat(2) with dirfd=AT_FDCWD and flags=0. POSIX
    explicitly defines unlink(path) as equivalent to unlinkat(AT_FDCWD,
    path, 0). This proc returns the unlinkat syscall number (35);
    callers reconstructing the unlink() shape must invoke as (AT_FDCWD,
    pathname, 0).

    Reference: Linux kernel include/uapi/asm-generic/unistd.h pins
    __NR_unlinkat at 35.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Returns the integer 35, the asm-generic __NR_unlinkat value. The
    kernel routine fs/namei.c::do_unlinkat is shared between unlink()
    and unlinkat() on architectures that retain both.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). Kernel-side cost dominated by directory-entry removal and
    inode-reference-count decrement; identical between unlink() and
    unlinkat() with flags=0.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Unlink is a privileged-relative operation: write permission on the
    parent directory is required, and sticky-bit semantics on
    world-writable directories restrict deletion to the file owner or
    root. These checks happen in the kernel during the actual syscall,
    not in this proc.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 35
End Process

Process called "riscv32_SYS_MKDIR" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Linux RISC-V 32-bit asm-generic numbering does not provide mkdir(2).
    The replacement is mkdirat(2) with dirfd=AT_FDCWD. POSIX defines
    mkdir(path, mode) as equivalent to mkdirat(AT_FDCWD, path, mode).
    This proc returns the mkdirat syscall number (34); callers
    reconstructing the mkdir() shape must invoke as (AT_FDCWD, pathname,
    mode).

    Reference: Linux kernel include/uapi/asm-generic/unistd.h pins
    __NR_mkdirat at 34.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Returns the integer 34, the asm-generic __NR_mkdirat value. Kernel
    routine fs/namei.c::do_mkdirat is the shared backend.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). Kernel-side cost dominated by directory inode allocation and
    parent-directory entry insertion; identical between mkdir() and
    mkdirat().
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The mode argument is masked by the process umask. Write permission
    on the parent directory is required. These checks happen in-kernel
    during the actual syscall.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 34
End Process

Process called "riscv32_SYS_RMDIR" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Linux RISC-V 32-bit asm-generic numbering does not provide rmdir(2).
    The replacement is unlinkat(2) with dirfd=AT_FDCWD and
    flags=AT_REMOVEDIR (0x200), which causes the kernel to treat the
    target as a directory and apply the rmdir() empty-directory check
    rather than the file unlink path. This proc returns the unlinkat
    syscall number (35); callers reconstructing the rmdir() shape must
    invoke as (AT_FDCWD, pathname, AT_REMOVEDIR).

    Reference: Linux kernel include/uapi/linux/fcntl.h defines
    AT_REMOVEDIR=0x200.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Returns the integer 35, the asm-generic __NR_unlinkat value (same
    syscall as SYS_UNLINK — the AT_REMOVEDIR flag differentiates them).
    The bridging discipline at the caller is: (AT_FDCWD, pathname,
    0x200). A caller that omits AT_REMOVEDIR triggers the file-unlink
    path on a directory inode and the kernel returns -EISDIR.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) syscall-dispatch cost. Kernel-side cost dominated by the
    empty-directory check (must scan the directory's . and .. entries
    to confirm no other children remain).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Write permission on the parent directory is required. Sticky-bit
    semantics apply identically to unlink. Removing a directory that
    is a process's current working directory has POSIX-defined behaviour
    (subsequent path resolutions from that cwd return -ENOENT) that is
    the caller's responsibility to handle.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 35
End Process

Note:
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
High-level Unix-portable syscall wrappers (dispatcher-exposed names)
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
:End Note

Process called "riscv32_syscall_fstat" takes fd as Integer, statbuf as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Dispatcher-API entry-point for POSIX fstat(2) on Linux RISC-V 32-bit.
    fstat operates on an already-open file descriptor (no path traversal),
    so unlike the path-based stat(2)/lstat(2), Linux RISC-V 32-bit retains
    a native asm-generic syscall for it (__NR_fstat = 80). This wrapper
    forwards the 2-arg fstat(fd, statbuf) shape directly to the kernel
    via syscall_2 with no AT_FDCWD bridging.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Calls SYS_FSTAT() to fetch the syscall number (returns 80), then
    invokes syscall_2 with (80, fd, statbuf). The inline-asm in syscall_2
    loads 80 into a7, fd into a0, statbuf into a1, issues ecall, and
    returns the kernel's a0 result. The statbuf points to a `struct stat`
    laid out per the kernel's asm-generic/stat.h definition (76-byte
    record on rv32 ilp32; 32-bit dev/ino/mode/nlink/uid/gid/rdev/blksize,
    32-bit size/blocks, and three 64-bit timespec triples for
    atime/mtime/ctime). No error translation; -errno is propagated to
    the caller verbatim.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Two procedure-call layers (syscall_fstat -> syscall_2) plus one
    ecall. The procedure-call overhead is the typical Runa Process-
    invocation cost; the kernel side cost dominates (one vfs_fstat call,
    one user-space struct copy). Inliner may collapse syscall_fstat to
    a direct syscall_2 invocation in a hot path.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    fd is validated by the kernel against the per-process file-descriptor
    table; bad fds return -EBADF. The statbuf pointer is validated via
    access_ok / copy_to_user; a bad pointer returns -EFAULT. fstat does
    NOT require path-traversal permission (the open fd is the
    authorisation token), so it is safe to call on any successfully
    opened file. This proc does no validation of its own.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let syscall_num be riscv32_SYS_FSTAT()
    Return riscv32_syscall_2(syscall_num, fd, statbuf)
End Process

Process called "riscv32_syscall_lseek" takes fd as Integer, offset as Integer, whence as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Dispatcher-API entry-point for POSIX lseek(2) on Linux RISC-V 32-bit.
    Routes through syscall_3 with the asm-generic __NR_lseek (62) and
    the standard lseek argument shape (fd, offset, whence). Whence
    selects how offset is interpreted: SEEK_SET (0) from start of file,
    SEEK_CUR (1) relative to current position, SEEK_END (2) relative to
    end of file. Return value is the resulting absolute offset on success
    or negative -errno on failure.

    Note on rv32 specifics: the asm-generic __NR_lseek entry expects a
    32-bit signed offset; for 64-bit file offsets, callers should invoke
    __NR_llseek (140) directly via syscall_5 with the hi/lo offset split
    convention defined by the ABI. The dispatcher contract only requires
    32-bit lseek here.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Calls SYS_LSEEK() to fetch the syscall number (returns 62), then
    invokes syscall_3 with (62, fd, offset, whence). The inline-asm in
    syscall_3 loads 62 into a7, fd into a0, offset into a1, whence into
    a2, issues ecall, and returns the kernel's a0 result. No error
    translation; -errno is propagated verbatim.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Two procedure-call layers (syscall_lseek -> syscall_3) plus one
    ecall. The kernel-side cost is dominated by the file-position
    update inside the kernel file table (a single atomic write to
    file->f_pos). Inliner may collapse syscall_lseek to a direct
    syscall_3 invocation in a hot path.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    fd is validated by the kernel (returns -EBADF on bad fd). Offset is
    not security-relevant on its own; the file content read/written at
    the resulting position is subject to the open-mode permissions
    granted at open() time. A caller that combines attacker-controlled
    offset with SEEK_END can yield a position prior to file start, which
    the kernel rejects with -EINVAL on conforming Linux. This proc does
    no validation of its own; the kernel enforces all invariants.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let syscall_num be riscv32_SYS_LSEEK()
    Return riscv32_syscall_3(syscall_num, fd, offset, whence)
End Process

Process called "riscv32_syscall_ioctl" takes fd as Integer, cmd as Integer, arg as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Dispatcher-API entry-point for POSIX ioctl(2) on Linux RISC-V 32-bit.
    Asm-generic __NR_ioctl is 29 (include/uapi/asm-generic/unistd.h,
    inherited unchanged by all newer Linux ports including rv32).
    Three-arg shape (fd, request, argp). The argp value is either a
    small integer command argument or a pointer to a request-specific
    structure (struct termios for TCGETS, struct winsize for
    TIOCGWINSZ, etc).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Composes the syscall by calling riscv32_SYS_IOCTL() (returns 29)
    and riscv32_syscall_3(29, fd, cmd, arg). The RV32 syscall
    convention loads 29 into a7, fd into a0, cmd into a1, arg into
    a2, then issues ecall; a0 holds the result on return as the
    canonical "negative-errno on failure" value.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Two procedure-call layers (syscall_ioctl -> syscall_3) plus one
    ecall. Kernel-side cost is one FD-table lookup and a driver
    vtable jump. Terminal queries (TCGETS, TIOCGWINSZ) are cheap
    memcpy-from-tty operations; callers should cache results across
    repeated queries.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The kernel validates fd against the FD table and dispatches cmd
    through file_operations.unlocked_ioctl. arg, if a pointer, is
    dereferenced by the kernel with the structure size implied by
    cmd; callers must size the buffer to match. This proc does no
    validation of its own; the kernel enforces all invariants.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let syscall_num be riscv32_SYS_IOCTL()
    Return riscv32_syscall_3(syscall_num, fd, cmd, arg)
End Process

Note:
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
POSIX file-mode constants (octal-to-decimal pre-decoded)
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
:End Note

@Reasoning
Linux file-permission modes are 12-bit octal bitfields combining read/
write/execute permissions for owner (bits 8-6), group (bits 5-3), and
other (bits 2-0), plus three high bits for setuid/setgid/sticky.
Standard symbolic flags (S_IRUSR=0400, S_IWUSR=0200, S_IRGRP=0040,
S_IWGRP=0020, S_IROTH=0004, S_IWOTH=0002, S_IXUSR=0100, S_IXGRP=0010,
S_IXOTH=0001) compose into common decimal values. 0644 = 0400|0200|
0040|0004 = 420 decimal. 0755 = 0400|0200|0100|0040|0010|0004|0001 =
493 decimal. RISC-V 32-bit inherits these values unchanged from the
Linux asm-generic permission model.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each accessor is a nullary Process returning the constant integer value.
The dispatcher's `MODE_0644 from Syscall` lookup resolves to this proc
on Linux RISC-V 32-bit targets via the bare-name route established in
Wave 1. Wave 2 will rename to `riscv32_MODE_0644`; Wave 1 keeps the
bare form to match the still-bare dispatcher.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
These accessors are constant returns; the compiler is expected to
inline them at every call site, leaving zero call overhead. Do not
introduce any runtime computation here.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning a file permission constant carries no security state. Callers
who use the returned value as a `mode` argument to creat/open(O_CREAT)/
mkdir/chmod are responsible for ensuring the requested permission
matches the intended access policy. World-readable (0644) is appropriate
for non-sensitive files; group-and-world-executable (0755) is
appropriate for binaries and directories.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "riscv32_MODE_0644" returns Integer:
    Return 420
End Process

Process called "riscv32_MODE_0755" returns Integer:
    Return 493
End Process

Note:
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
lseek whence constants
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
:End Note

@Reasoning
The `whence` argument to lseek(2) selects how the supplied offset is
interpreted: SEEK_SET (0) measures from the start of the file, SEEK_CUR
(1) measures relative to the current file position, SEEK_END (2)
measures relative to end-of-file. Linux RISC-V 32-bit inherits the same
values as every Linux architecture, defined in include/uapi/linux/fs.h
and the POSIX specification. These match the bare-name dispatcher's
expectations and the syscall_lseek wrapper's whence parameter.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Nullary Process accessors returning the constant integer values. The
dispatcher routes `SEEK_SET from Syscall` to this proc on riscv32
targets via the bare-name pattern still in force during Wave 1. Bodies
are non-side-effecting and trivially inlinable.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant returns; compiler-inlined at the call site. No runtime cost.
Avoid wrapping these in additional indirection; the dispatcher already
selects the platform-correct value at the dispatch boundary.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning a seek-whence constant has no security implications on its
own. Callers that pass user-influenced offset values into lseek with
these whence flags MUST validate the resulting absolute file position
against the file's permitted range; an attacker-controlled negative
offset combined with SEEK_END can yield an unexpected position prior
to file start, which lseek will reject with EINVAL on conforming
Linux kernels.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "riscv32_SEEK_SET" returns Integer:
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "riscv32_SEEK_CUR" returns Integer:
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "riscv32_SEEK_END" returns Integer:
    Return 2
End Process

Note:
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Additional open(2) flag constants
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
:End Note

@Reasoning
open(2) and openat(2) accept a flags bitfield combining access mode
(O_RDONLY/O_WRONLY/O_RDWR, defined earlier) with creation/status flags
(O_CREAT, O_TRUNC, O_APPEND, plus the rarer O_EXCL/O_NONBLOCK/O_SYNC).
On Linux these values are defined in include/uapi/asm-generic/fcntl.h
and inherited by RISC-V 32-bit unchanged from the asm-generic table:
O_CREAT=0100 octal = 64 decimal, O_TRUNC=01000 octal = 512 decimal,
O_APPEND=02000 octal = 1024 decimal. Callers combine these via bitwise
OR to express the full open-mode intent.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each accessor is a nullary Process returning the asm-generic flag
value. The dispatcher's `O_CREAT from Syscall` lookup resolves to this
proc on riscv32 targets via the bare-name route. Wave 2 will rename to
`riscv32_O_CREAT`; Wave 1 keeps the bare form. These values are stable
since Linux 2.6 and form part of the kernel/userland ABI.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant returns; compiler-inlined at every call site. No runtime cost.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Flag constants carry no security state on their own. However, the
combinations callers construct have direct security implications:
O_CREAT without O_EXCL can race with attacker-created symlinks
(TOCTOU); O_TRUNC on a file the caller does not own can destroy data
the caller did not intend to modify; O_APPEND is the only reliable way
to atomically append to a log file under concurrent writers. These
discipline concerns are the caller's responsibility; this proc only
provides the numeric value.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "riscv32_O_CREAT" returns Integer:
    Return 64
End Process

Process called "riscv32_O_TRUNC" returns Integer:
    Return 512
End Process

Process called "riscv32_O_APPEND" returns Integer:
    Return 1024
End Process

Note:
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Memory protection flags (mmap/mprotect `prot` argument)
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
:End Note

@Reasoning
The `prot` argument to mmap(2) and mprotect(2) is a bitfield selecting
page-level access permissions: PROT_NONE (0, page inaccessible — any
access faults with SIGSEGV), PROT_READ (1, reads permitted), PROT_WRITE
(2, writes permitted), PROT_EXEC (4, instruction fetch permitted).
Linux RISC-V 32-bit inherits these values from
include/uapi/asm-generic/mman-common.h unchanged. Flags compose via
bitwise OR (e.g. PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE = 3 for read-write data pages).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each accessor is a nullary Process returning the asm-generic protection
value. The dispatcher's `PROT_READ from Syscall` lookup resolves to
this proc on riscv32 targets via the bare-name route. Wave 2 will
rename to `riscv32_PROT_READ`. The numeric values are part of the
kernel/userland ABI and have been stable across Linux's lifetime.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant returns; compiler-inlined at every call site. The kernel-side
cost of installing the protection bits during mmap or mprotect is
O(pages_in_range) and is unaffected by the proc-level constant return.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Memory protection flags are a fundamental security primitive. PROT_EXEC
on writable mappings creates W^X violations exploitable for code
injection; callers should split into a PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE phase
followed by mprotect-to-PROT_READ|PROT_EXEC after content is written
(W xor X). PROT_NONE pages are used for guard regions to detect
stack/heap overflows. The kernel enforces these flags via the MMU
page-table protection bits; userland cannot bypass them without a
kernel exploit.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "riscv32_PROT_NONE" returns Integer:
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "riscv32_PROT_READ" returns Integer:
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "riscv32_PROT_WRITE" returns Integer:
    Return 2
End Process

Process called "riscv32_PROT_EXEC" returns Integer:
    Return 4
End Process

Note:
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Memory mapping flags (mmap `flags` argument)
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
:End Note

@Reasoning
The `flags` argument to mmap(2) selects mapping visibility and
placement semantics: MAP_SHARED (1, writes propagate to the backing
file and are visible to other mappings of the same file), MAP_PRIVATE
(2, writes use copy-on-write and are not visible elsewhere), MAP_FIXED
(0x10 = 16, interpret addr exactly rather than as a hint), MAP_ANONYMOUS
(0x20 = 32, mapping is not backed by any file — used for heap/stack/
arena allocation). Linux RISC-V 32-bit inherits these values from
include/uapi/asm-generic/mman-common.h and include/uapi/asm-generic/
mman.h. MAP_SHARED and MAP_PRIVATE are mutually exclusive (exactly one
must be specified); the remaining flags compose via bitwise OR.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each accessor is a nullary Process returning the asm-generic mapping
flag value. The dispatcher's `MAP_PRIVATE from Syscall` lookup resolves
to this proc on riscv32 targets via the bare-name route. Wave 2 will
rename to `riscv32_MAP_PRIVATE`. The numeric values are stable
kernel/userland ABI. Note: MAP_ANONYMOUS pairs with fd=-1 and offset=0
in conforming portable code; the rv32 kernel ignores fd/offset when
MAP_ANONYMOUS is set but POSIX-strict portability demands the -1/0
pair.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant returns; compiler-inlined at every call site. The kernel-side
cost of establishing the mapping is O(pages) for the page-table setup;
the choice of MAP_PRIVATE vs MAP_SHARED determines whether subsequent
writes incur the COW-fault penalty (MAP_PRIVATE) or direct write-back
(MAP_SHARED, with dirty-page tracking).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
MAP_FIXED is security-sensitive: it requests that the kernel place the
mapping at a specific address, potentially overwriting an existing
mapping (the kernel will unmap the existing region without warning).
Modern code should use MAP_FIXED_NOREPLACE (0x100000, added in Linux
4.17) instead. MAP_SHARED on a file the caller has write access to
permits in-place modification of file contents — relevant to mandatory
access control policies. MAP_ANONYMOUS pages are zero-filled by the
kernel on first access (a security guarantee preventing data leakage
from previously-freed pages).
@End Security_Scope

Process called "riscv32_MAP_SHARED" returns Integer:
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "riscv32_MAP_PRIVATE" returns Integer:
    Return 2
End Process

Process called "riscv32_MAP_FIXED" returns Integer:
    Return 16
End Process

Process called "riscv32_MAP_ANONYMOUS" returns Integer:
    Return 32
End Process
